column168: A Quick Fuel Fleet Services driver placed approximately 40 gallons of diesel fuel within a tank located on a piece of construction equipment called a "Steam Roller" at approximately 0001 on August 9, 2014. During the early morning hours of 8/9/14 the diesel fuel seeped out of the steam roller tank onto the surrounding ground surface comprised of soil and gravel. Construction workers notified Quick Fuel Fleet Services when they arrived at the constructions site during the morning of 8/9/14 and observed the diesl fuel impacted soil. TAS Environmental Services personnel were dispatched to the site to clean up the diesel fuel impacted soil. TAS removed approximately 12 cubic yards of diesel impacted soil for disposal. Soil samples were collected from the resulting excavation to be analyzed for total petroleum hydrocarbns (TPH). The excavation was then backfilled with clean fill material.
column169: Quick Fuel Fleet Services driver was trained not to place diesel fuel within the same tank compartment of the steam roller in the future.

On 08/01/2014 at 1320 personnel with CSX Intermodal Jacksonville Terminal discovered  CMCU495234, a loaded container of Env Haz Sub Liq NOS in 55gals drums leaked approx 3gals liquid on bottom of container and minium drops on asphalt pavement. The container was isolated and NRC report 1090974 and FL EMA report 2014-5402 were notified. The shipper, Crowley Liner Svcs representatives Mike Lesser and Keith Satterwhite 904-727-2391 was notified by CSXI Cust Service. Hulls Environmental, CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found one 55gal drum leaked 3gals product due to drum damaged on bottom. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the leak with absorbent materials, deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the material. All lading put back in original freight container with proper load/block/brace and released to the shipper.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident did not require a Form 7.1.

column168: CN Transportation Department employee noted liquid coming from tank car GATX 61293 (Load: Hydrochloric Acid, UN1789) during an inbound inspections at the CN Markham Yard, Markham, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting security seals in tact. All pressure plate bolts were loose allowing product to escape. Bolts securing the pressure plate to the nozzle were tightened and car pressure tested. Car leaked at 3.5 psig. Car was transferred by shipper and exterior cleaned.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: CN Mechanical department employee noted product coming from the top of tank car UTLX 23461 (L / Methanol, UN 1230) during an  inspection at the CN Baton Rouge Yard, Baton Rouge, LA. All appropriate departments notified, tank car was isolated. CN's response team responded noting liquid coming from the combination housing. The combination housing was secured by seal #IMTT 180244.  The seal was removed and upon opening the housing, liquid was observed coming from the flange below the liquid line valve.  The bolts on the flange were checked for tightness and were found to be loose.  The bolts were tightened and the leak stopped.
column169: No additional comments.

column25: AGSI Systems LLC - Dan Francis Crowland
column62: Dropped; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: On August 7, 2014 at approximately 1300hrs a Federal Express (FedEx) delivery was made to the Lockheed Martin facility located at 7121 Standard Drive Hanover, Maryland.  During this delivery of packages it was noted that several boxes were damaged.  This was apparently due to the weight of the box content (~87 lbs>).  It was at this time that Lockheed Martin receiving personnel observed the contents of the boxes.  They were identified as Lithium Metal Batteries.  Receiving personnel immediately contacted the Lockheed Martin warehouse lead and Environmental Safety & Health personnel.     There was no indication that the boxes contained Lithium Metal batteries.  There were no Hazardous Material markings/labels on the boxes nor did any of the shipping documents list the contents.  It was only due to the physical condition of the packaging that the contents were discovered.
column169: Representatives of AGSI Systems should be notified and instructed on the proper packaging and shipping requirements for hazardous materials such as the Lithium Metal Batteries received at Lockheed Martin.  Additionally, the UPS Store in Fountain, CO should also receive similar instruction on shipping such materials.

column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. truck was at a shipper's location in the process of loading multiple waste streams of drummed waste. During the loading process a drum was observed to have a minor leak at the bottom weld/seam. The leak appeared to be caused by corrosion of the drum material being caused by the waste the drum contained. The shipper was notified and all 6 drums of the waste stream were rejected for transportation. The shipper performed their own clean-up and the drums were left on site. The Oregon Emergency Management Division was notified. OEMD report #2014-1727.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the drums for transportation no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum, re containerize, or reject before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the incident. The shipper explained that they recently had a change in their production process that impacted the PH of the waste. The Clean Harbors waste profile for this waste stream has been frozen and will no longer be accepted for transportation pending re characterization and approval of a new profile.

column168: On August 7, 2014 at approximately 09:14 personnel in the CSXT Langhorne yard discovered UTLX 207136, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Crude Oil leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper Musket Corp Thad Davis 405-302-6582 local, state and/or federal agencies as applicable were notified CHEMTREC Report # 2014-08-07-00088. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the reclosing pressure relief device had a broken stem. The PRD was a UTC 501605 06 serial# 38503, 165 psi. Contractor personnel bagged the PRD to keep rain out; the car was moved to a location in the yard to be repaired. Musket was advised to have a mobile repair company change out the valve and request an OTMA to move car to PES to be offloaded, then home shopped to be leak tested. The spilled material was cleaned off the car.    This car did have a special move to set out of main line train  This incident will require a 7.1    NARRI=418  5X (5+5+0) X (2+0) =100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On August 4th, 2014 at 1727 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered TCIX 16035, a loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide Solution, UN 1824, leaking product from the jacket area near the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the shipper Olin Corporation was notified, Rep. John Gabryelski, 716-870-1887, CHEMTREC Report 2014-08-04-00209, EP+S of Vermont, the Buffalo Branch, a CSX emergency response contractor was dispatched, as was CSX HazMat Manager Michael Bethge.  Upon inspection product was found to be dripping from between the jacket and a brake rigging attachment assembly, approximately 24 inches in toward the B-end of the tank car from the Bottom Outlet Valve, a Haz-Hammock was placed under the dripping area to contain the product release. The tank car was moved to a secure location, a calf car was identified and on August 5th, 2014 Olin Corp. conducted a transfer of product from TCIX 16035.  On August 13th, 2014 EP+S of Vermont conducted a clean + purge process on TCIX 16035 to remove all residue product from the tank car, and cut away the jacket area for inspection to identify the release point.   At present a visual review identified a crack in the weld seam on the B-R weld pad, located at the outer edge of the weld to the tank shell of the skid plate protection mounting point, see attached photos.      This car did require a special move.    Cause Code: 652 (2 points)  NARRI: 2x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 40

column168: On August 13th, 2014 at 07:44 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered TRFX 1488, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Hess Trading Corporation, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-08-13-00067. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the release was between manway swing bolts 2 + 3 area of the manway cover, the gasket was inspected and found to have a deep crack in the face of the gasket, the gasket was replaced, the nozzle was wipe down and the cover was re-secured and tool tightened.  Mr. Jody Schroeder, Hess Trading Corp. Oil gathering Supt., Office: 701-664-6402 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. TRFX 1488 was released for transport.    This incident did NOT require a special move.    Cause Code: 209 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On August 13th, 2014 at 09:50 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered TRFX 1450, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Hess Trading Corporation, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-08-13-00067. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the release was between manway cover swing bolts 1 and 8 at the hinge, all the swing were tool tight, the manway was opened, the gasket was inspected and found no exceptions, but the gasket was wet and showing oily residue, therefore it would be considered a misaligned manway cover. The nozzle was wiped down and the cover was re-secured and tool tightened.  Mr. Jody Schroeder, Hess Trading Corp. Oil gathering Supt., Office: 701-664-6402 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. TRFX 1450 was released for transport.    This incident did NOT require a special move.    Cause Code: 662 (2 points) Other Description: Manway Hinged + Bolted                                                                             Connection between manway nozzle +                                                                             manway cover.                                                                             Bolts/Nuts Tool Tight - Cover Misaligned,                                                                             not torqued in sequence.  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: During a BNSF mechanical inspection in the railyard, tank car GATX 90924 was observed dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. Containment was placed under GATX 90924 to catch the drippage. Contract responders reported the leak source was at the BOV mounting flange connection. All four mounting flange bolts/nuts were found less than tool tight and these flange bolts/nuts were tool tightened (one at 3/4 turn and 3 at 1/4 turn ) until the commodity drips ceased  by 1500 hrs. CDT, 8/07/2014. GATX 90924 continued to be monitored to ensure no further leakage resurfaced.  Spill impacted ballast/soils were neutralized with a citric acid solution and then hand excavated. All spill impacted and clean-up materials were placed into a 55 gallon poly disposal drum and earmarked for appropriate disposal. Response was concluded by 1830 hrs. CDT 8/07/2014. It should be noted that GATX 90924 completed its 10 year tank qualification on 7/10/2014 and was on its first loaded trip after qualification.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A roll-off container operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services (CHES), Inc. was staged at Clean Harbors temporary storage facility in Baltomore MD en route from  the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility. Upon a routine inspection of the containment area a CHES employee discovered a small  amount of material coming from the rear door of the roll-off container. A CHES response crew opened the roll off door, added sorbent and resealed the rear  door identified as the cause of the release. The effected spill area was cleaned and added to the container then secured for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The CHES team involved in shipping this container were advised of the incident and retraining was insituted regarding packaging, load preparation, blocking and bracing/load securment to assure the conditions of the special permit are followed to prevent and further incidents.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. parked at Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location in Bristol, CT for the purpose of  consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. Upon routine  inspection, it was discovered that approximately 1/2 gallon of material escaped from the container. Response personnel donning personal protective  equipment placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from the van trailer. The container was secured and  was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility. All required local and state reports were made that included verbal reports to the  Connecticut Department of Environmental Protection and local Fire Department.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum, re-containerize or reject drums before transportation is initiated.

column168: On August 13, 2014, at 09:12 hours, a Trainmaster for the CSXT Benwood Yard, Benwood, West Virginia reported that an FRA Hazardous Material Inspector took exception to CITX 221078, a loaded tank car of UN1203, Gasoline. The tank car was reported to have product on the sides from the breadbox area. It was isolated. The shipper, Williams Ohio Valley Midstream, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2014-08-13-00088. SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Benwood Yard. SPSI found the leak was originating from between the flange of the tank car and the pressure plate for the breadbox.  There were no loose bolts and the gap was sealed with a sealant material for an emergency move under One Time Movement Approval FRA140813R2V granted by the FRA. The shipper representative, Brian Cava,  780 449 9780, was notified of the situation found. Tank car CITX 221078 was returned to the facility on August 14, 2014 at 22:30.  This incident did require a special move.    NARRI: 5x(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 80  Cause code:221

Facility personnel stated the trailer was received and it was discovered that product is leaking from the top cap/bung. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate ETA to scene of 90 minutes. The shipper is Chemtreat. ERTS has requested copies of the MSDS and BOL. The contractor advises on site and stated it appears the bung has been ripped off the cap resulting in the release of approximately 2 ounces of the product. Clean up operations are underway.. The contractor reports they are completed with the clean up of the impacted tote and they were able to replace the cap/bung. The replacement cap/bung is secure and no further release was observed.

Driver was traveling south on US Hwy 287 between Corsicana, Texas, and approximately 15 miles north of Palestine, Tx. The driver had loaded UN1075 product at O'Ryan Oil & Gas(Texon) in Powell, Texas and was traveling to the ELTM facility in Oakwood, Texas to deliver. While traveling on Hwy 287 the driver came upon a thunderstorm. Rain was heavy and the trailer traveled off of the right shoulder. When the driver tried to bring the trailer back onto the road, the product shift created the roll over of the unit. The trailer slid to the right and detached from the fifth wheel of the truck and rolled onto the right shoulder and ditch, coming to rest near a fence. The driver notified 911 and proceeded to call management and contain the scene. The driver inspected the trailer and found no leaks or structural failures and reported this to local officials and his supervisor. Upon notification of incident, reporting procedures were followed to include Federal and State notifications were made. There were no injuries, deaths, or product release during this incident.

column168: Tank car ACFX 86864 in the railyard was reported dripping commodity from the area near its bottom outlet valve (BOV). Portable containment was placed under ACFX 86864 to capture drippage. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspecting ACFX 86864 reported the leak source was at the area of the saddle welds (BOV mounting flange welded to the tank bottom) towards the B-end direction. The saddle weld at the leak area measured approximately 5/8 inch wide by 10-11 inches in length; a pinhole crack within this weld area was suspected, although not specifically located. Contract responders attempted to seal this leak using 'Plug N Dike' sealant, but were unsuccessful in stopping the dripping. ACFX 86864 was carefully moved and isolated over the facility's containment pit with additional containment placed under the BOV to capture the commodity dripping down the outside of the BOV.  Commodity spillage in the railyard evaporated.  Contract responders transferred the remaining commodity within ACFX 86864 into four tank trucks on 8/06/2014 without further incident.  After the transfer was completed the commodity drips ceased.  Spillage in the containment pit was diluted by two rain events that occurred while ACFX 86864 was awaiting commodity transfer. The liquid in the containment pit was vacuumed and processed at the facility's waste water treatment plant on 8/7/2014.

column168: A rear dome lid of a hazardous waste tanker, # 0265, had not been securely fastened.  During transport the waste material within the tanker, encouraged by the “start and stop” movement of the vehicle, leaked out through this unsecure rear dome lid into the spill box surrounding it.  The material traveled down the drain tube, connected at the bottom of the spill box, and out the back of the tanker in a “mist” droplet size.  Larger quantities of material were spilled during stopping and starting specifically at the end of exit ramp # 59, exiting I-70 west onto SR 39, and during parking the tanker at the Loves truck stop.      A dry adsorbent material was spread over the affected areas of the exit ramp, route to Loves Truck stop SR 39, side road, Kroger way and the area of Loves truck stop where the tanker was parked.  The adsorbent material was collected, drummed and removed from the site.  A total of five drums were used to collect all of the sorbent material used to contain/remove the material released
column169: The responsible driver was suspended for five working days and has been retrained on following the established pre-inspection procedure for securing a tanker for hazardous material transport.  Further, a lessons learned of this incident plus behavior modification  shall be emphasized with all Hazardous Material drivers to "not assume that hatches and lids are secure until they have been verified as secure." Additionally it shall be reemphasized that it is the recognized responsibility of the transporting driver to ensure that all hatches and dome lids have be verified as closed and sealed prior to transporting.

column168: On August 20th, 2014 at 07:00 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered SHPX 222504, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car, coming from around the protective housing area. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Irving Oil Terminals, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-08-20-00065. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the release was between the tank car service nozzle and the protective housing/valve mounting service pressure plate. The securement bolts were checked and found to be tool tight, SHPX 222504 was secured with an oil absorbent boom section to mitigate any release to the environment, it is awaiting a transfer of the product and Home Shop disposition.  Mr. Matthew Douthwright, a manager for Irving Oil Terminals, Office: 506-647-7126 was notified of the situation found, and the action taken to secure the tank car while awaiting transfer.    This incident did require a special move.    Cause Code: 221 (5 points)  NARRI: 2x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 40

column168: The outbound train crew of entrained tank car UTLX 299036 in the railyard reported that it was emanating a commodity odor. A BNSF mechanical visual inspection of UTLX 299036 revealed commodity had leaked from its manway closure onto its top side shell. Contract responders arrived and observed that UTLX 299036's manway cover was not seated flush against the manway nozzle. A detailed inspection of the manway closure revealed that the manway securement eyebolts were not uniformly tightened (the eyebolts on one side of the manway cover were tighter than the other side that were looser). The installed manway gasket was found to be grooved on the side were the eyebolts were very tight and not providing a good seal. The manway gasket was replaced and the manway securement eyebolts were properly tool tightened in the recommended pattern.  All other valves and fittings were found secure. Non-evaporated spillage around the manway nozzle was wiped. Intact shipper seals Uline 3068166 and 3068165 were replaced with seals numbered 051398 and 051395 respectively. Response was concluded by 2100 hrs. CDT, 8/13/2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 08/27/2014 at 2143hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal Jacksonville Terminal discovered CMCU208779, a loaded container of Environmentally  Hazardous Substances, Liquid N.O.S. in 55 gallon drums leaked approximately 1gallon of liquid from rear of container with minimum drops on asphalt pavement. The container was isolated and NRC, report#1093689 and FL EMA report,  2014-6028 were notified. The shipper, Crowley Liner Services representatives Mike Lesser and Keith Satterwhite 904-727-2391 was notified by CSXI Customer Service. Hulls Environmental, CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found one 55 gallon drum leaked 1 gallon of product due to drum damaged on top head-bung. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the leak with absorbent materials, deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the material. The original freight container with proper load/block/brace was released to the shipper.      This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident did not require a Form 7.1..

column25: Interdom LLC for Lonza (Mapleton Bulk Amines)
column168: Intermodal tank container CLGU 250001 was reported possibly leaking commodity. CLGU 250001 was carefully moved and isolated at the facility's containment area. Contract responders inspecting CLGU 250001 reported finding all 8 manway cover securement wing nuts loose with one of these with a cracked wing extension.  Five wing nuts were two full turns loose with the remaining three wing nuts extremely loose.  The responders secured all loose wing nuts by 1510 hrs. PDT, 8/24/2014 which ended any further release of commodity from the manway closure. This was confirmed during re-inspection after subsequent container movements within the facility. All spillage remained confined within the spillbox area surrounding the manway closure. The small amount of non-evaporated and dried residue spillage was wiped.
column169: Shippers were notified of tank container CLGU 250001's manway securement deficiencies and these securement issues will be addressed for corrective action going forward.

column168: While performing inspection of van trailers on site, red liquid material was observed leaking from underneath van trailer #509037.  The van contained 55 gallon drums shipped from Qualawash.  The manifest was reviewed and confirmed with the placarding on the trailer.  The trailer was moved to the loading dock.  The drums were unloaded until the leaking drum was identified.  The drum contained flammable solvents (Xylene/Toluene listed in the shipping description). The drum had no ruptures, dents, or otherwise any other sign of damage.  The side and top of the drum showed evidence of leaking material.  The bung and ring closure were inspected and found to be tight, however, the contents of the drum had expanded in the heat during storage on the trailer and leaked out the top bung and from around the ring closure. Approximately 0.5 gallons of material was estimated to have leaked.  The leaking drum was overpacked into a salvage drum.  The leaked material was cleaned up with absorbent and placed inside the salvage drum, and then the van trailer was re-loaded, and transported to the Veolia Port Arthur Facility for disposal.
column169: The Veolia Account Manager will communicate with Qualawash regarding the incident and reccomend they review their filling procedures and training and ensure that adequate head space is left in drums of organic solvents, especially during hot weather.

column168: Driver was traveling at an unsafe speed and failed to negotiate a right curve. The truck crossed the center line and drove off the left side of the roadway striking a tree with its front left side and caused the truck and trailer to disconnect. The truck stayed upright and the trailer overturned on its right side and spilled out 180 bbls of crude oil due to the force of the impact. The force caused the dome lid to pop off and the bands broke near the rear of the trailer spilling the oil. The oil spilled out at a very high rate of speed with the dome having been popped off. Estimated duration of release five minutes. A environmental clean up was called immediately. Not much could be done to mitigate the release but every measure has been taken to clean it up.
column169: We have terminated the driver for unsafe driving. We spend two weeks with every driver at hire to train them in safe driving and being aware of hazards. They take the smith systems defensive driving coarse at hire and spend one week in classroom training. Then they spend six days with a driver trainer learning how to properly and safely operate a vehicle. We have standard operating procedures and driving practices in our fleet safety manuals that are issued to every driver and they are trained on during their first two weeks. We also pull MVRs, do annual reviews, and follow them on Peoplenet, our electronic onboard recorders. This driver was found to be under the influence of drugs and alcohol. All our drivers are given pre-employments and pulled at random at a rate of 100% for the year. We take and will continue to take very precaution necessary to prevent this in the future.

column168: During a routine yard check at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a tote was found to have leaked some liquid onto the ground in the containment area. The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.

column168: On August 27, 2014 at 11:08 hours personnel in the Worthville/Carrollton Yard discovered GATX 72992, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Axiall Corp, was notified via CHEMTREC Report # 2014-0827-00165. Joseph McCann, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, found product leaking from 2 separate flanges on the liquid line assembly due to mounting flange bolts being less than tool tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative, Matt Bond 304-455-6708.  The mounting flange bolts were tightened, however, the release could not be secured.  The contents of the tank car were transloaded on site and the liquid line assembly, including the liquid line induction pipe, was removed from the car and a blind flange was installed.  The car will be moved to home shop for repair once the shipper has obtained the necessary OTMA.  A special switching move was required.  A QA 7.1 will be filed. column168: local FAA agent working on this is orde.duplessis@faa.gov  847-294-8107     The shipment was very poorly prepared for air transport and did not meet the requirements of the packaging instructions and exceeded the quantities allowed for transport on a passenger aircraft. column168: On 8/08/2014, the BNSF was notified that tank car PLCX 221754 was dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) while in the BNSF Butte railyard. Prior to this notification, PLCX 221754 was interchanged by BNSF to the RARW (Rarus Rwy. Co.) in Butte on 7/30/2014. The RARW alleges it never took possession of PLCX 221754 due to the leaking BOV. The BNSF called contract responders to inspect and secure PLCX 221754. Responder's inspection of PLCX 221754 revealed that the BOV was in the closed position. The commodity droplets were dripping from this valve's cap assembly's closure plug area and the likelihood of liquid by-passing the closed bottom outlet valve was suspected.  The BOV's closure plug was found not tool tight and responders tool tightened this closure plug by 1/2 full turn which stopped the commodity dripping by 1615 hrs. MDT, 8/08/2014. Afterwards, all surfaces encompassing the BOV were decontaminated. Ground impacted soils under the BOV were hand shoveled and placed into a poly disposal drum for appropriate future disposal.   PLCX 221754 continued to be monitored with no further commodity dripping observed. Response was concluded by 1930 hrs. MDT, 8/08/2014.

column168: On August 26, 2014, at 0948 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Collinwood Yard, Cleveland, Ohio reported that an FRA Hazardous Material Inspector took exception to GATX 90905, a loaded tank car of UN1814, Potassium Hydroxide, Solution. Reportedly there was product around and inside of the reclosing pressure relief device PRD. The tank car was removed from the outbound train and isolated. The shipper, Ashta Chemicals, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2014-08-26-00098. Sunpro, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Collinwood Yard. Sunpro found that the PRD was in fact releasing product and would need to be replaced prior to continuing in transportation. The shipper representative, Jeanne Kochevar, 440-997-6862 was notified of the situation found. Ashta Chemicals is having a mobile repair facility replace the faulty PRD and will move under One Time Movement Approval if requalification of the tank car is impractical. GATX 90905 is currently on hold pending the appropriate actions.  This incident did require a special move.  NARRI: 2x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 40  Cause code:664

column168: JBH vehicle was reported leaking shortly after leaving the shipper's facility; the leaking material was described as a dark purple color. We broke the seal and began unloading the cargo looking for the source of the leak; cargo was noted to be packed high in the unit.  The leaking IBC was near the nose of the trailer.  The cause of the spill was a wooden pallet with cargo that had been placed atop the IBC.  Being a non-load bearing structure, the pallet was able to press down on top of the cap, causing it to leak on estimated 15 gallons of class 8 PG III.  The vendor was not initially able to confirm if it was corrosive leaking as the dye made it impossible to read the litmus paper the vendor had brought with them.  Subsequent analysis of photos of the cargo confirmed it was corrosive that was leaking.  Our hazmat vendor remediated the spill, repackaged the leaking contents and disposed of the subsequently-generated hazardous waste.
column169: The shipper has been suspended from shipping hazmat with JBH pending review of their loading & securement techniques.  This spill was caused by shipper negligence; in my opinion it was quite careless and irresponsible for them to have loaded a pallet on top of an IBC of class 8 hazmat.

column168: (A)On August 29th, 2014 at 15:04 hours, personnel at the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered ACFX 76586, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, DPTS Marketing, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-08-29-00170. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo Branch office was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that manway cover swing bolts #1 + 2 were Less Than Tool Tight and the gasket was not seated properly, this caused a release of product between the manway cover gasket and the nozzle, the lid gasket was inspected and found to be the wrong diameter and was deformed, the gasket was replaced with a nozzle type gasket, the manway cover was re-secured and tool tightened.  Mr. Paul Ferguson, Rail Logistics Manager, Cell: 612-849-0628 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. ACFX 76586 was released for transport. This incident did not require a special move. Cause Code: 200 (5 points) 211 (5 points) NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0)  = 100  (B)On August 29th, 2014 at 15:04 hours, personnel at the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered ACFX 76564, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, DPTS Marketing, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-08-29-00170. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo Branch office was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that all manway cover swing bolts where tool tight, but the manway cover gasket was not seated properly, this caused a release of product between the manway cover and the nozzle, the lid gasket was inspected and found to be the wrong diameter and was deformed, the gasket was replaced with a nozzle type gasket, the manway cover was re-secured and tool tightened.  Mr. Paul Ferguson, Rail Logistics Manager, Cell: 612-849-0628 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. ACFX 76564 was released for transport. On 08/26/2014 at 18:26 hours, Roselake Yard Yardmaster, Jeff Coffman, reported a Carman discovered CHIU252090, a loaded Intermodal Bulk Container of Hazardous Waste, Solid, NOS, leaking from the bottom of the container as it was punctured from the inside out. The container was isolated removed from the flatcar into secondary containment and the shipper, Clean Harbors Environmental from Kimball, NE, was notified. Environmental Restoration, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the container was punctured from the inside out. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Clean Harbors Environmental (Telephone #: 773-842-1582). Contractor personnel fixed the problem and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured. The incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 662    NARRI:   A (B+C+D) x (E+F)  2 (5+1+1) x (2+0) = 28

column168: AT 10:32 THE PACKAGE EITHER FELL OR WAS DROPPED INSIDE THE PACKAGE CAR AND BEGIN TO LEAK. THE DRIVER WRAPPED THE BOX INSIDE THREE DRIVER RELEASE BAGS, FINISHED THEIR ROUTE, AND PLACED THE LEAKING BOTTLE INSIDE. A UPS TOTE ON THE FLOOR OF METRO 4 ADJACENT TO THE TULSA NORTH CLERK'S STATION. A CLERK CALLED FOR A RESPONDER WHO WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SPILL SITE. AFTER MAKING SURE THE LIQUID DID NOT LEAK OUTSIDE THE DRIVER RELEASE BAGS THE RESPONDER BROUGHT THE BOX BACK TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA.  THE BOX DID NOT HAVE ANY HAZARDOUS MARKINGS, MSDS OR SHIPPING PAPERS. WHEN THE RESPONDER OPENED THE BOX HE SAW ONE OF THE PRODUCTS HAD A DOT CLASS 8 DIAMOND LABEL & HAZARDOUS MARKINGS. THE RESPONDER REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE HAZMAT SUPPORT CENTER. THE HAZMAT SUPPORT REP SAID IT WAS A POSSIBLE UNDECLARED HAZMAT AND GAVE THE RESPONDER A REFERENCE NUMBER AND DETAILED INSTRUCTIONS.

On August 9, 2014, QC Energy Resources Texas, LLC reported that the driver of CTMV #105119 loaded the CTMV using a flow meter mounted to the CTMV. When the meter reached the target the driver stopped loading and observed crude oil release. Upon further inspection the driver determined that the CTMV was full and the flow meter had malfunctioned. Approximately 2-3 barrels of crude oil released due to the flow meter malfunction.The crude oil impacted the gravel and soil at the Robins Well Site near Douglas, WY. The crude oil was unloaded so there was legal ullage in the CTMV. ERTS dispatched a contractor who  arrived on site at 12:05 EST to begin excavation.  10 yards  of crude oil contaminated gravel and dirt was  taken for disposal.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Tank car GATX 79883 standing on the facility's repair track to correct air brake defects was reported emanating a commodity odor. GATX 79883 was cordoned-off. A BNSF hazardous material responder inspecting GATX 79883 reported finding its liquid valve partially open with its closure plug not sealing in the valve port due to worn threads on the plug. These conditions allowed liquid commodity to escape at the liquid valve's closure. The responder closed the liquid valve and secured a replacement closure plug in the valve port. All spillage evaporated.   Also noted during GATX 79883's inspection was five of the applied manway cover securement eyebolts were not tool tight with the sixth eyebolt hanging or not applied. The responder properly secured all six manway cover eyebolts to a tool tight condition. Two of four applied placards were faded and these were replaced. The side specification stenciling was peeling and becoming nearly illegible.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: AT 19:00 IN THE EARTH CITY, MO HUB A LEAKING HAZMAT WAS FOUND ON THE SD 1-2 LOADING DOCK. THE BOX (A 12X12X12 275LBS BURTING TET FIDER BOARD BOX) WAS ON ITS SIDE, WET AND DISCOLORED. THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE ON THE GROUND FROM THE LEAK. THE CARTON SHOWED NO SIGNS OF ABUSE FROM THE SHIPPING PROCESS. THE HAZMAT WAS CONTAINED AND TRANSPORTED TOTHE DMP PROCESSING AREA. AN INTERNAL INSPECTION REVEALED NO PACKING MATERIAL TO PROTECT THE INNER RECEPTICLE (A 5 GALLON PLASTIC BLADDER). THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS A COMBINATION OF THE PACKAGE BEING PLACED ON ITS SIDE AND A LOOSE CAP. ALL MATERIAL HAS BEEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE UPS DAMAGED MATERIAL PROGRAM.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: On August 19, 2014, the carrier (Seaboard Marine) was advised by the shipper (Myron Bowling Auctioneers, Inc) that undeclared hazardous materials were stowed inside container TGHU913583-2 (UN2794 BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) received notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded.  Upon receiving notice from the shipper we immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and subsequently released for transportation

During a routine check of the Clean Harbors 10 day storage facility in Newark NJ a very small leak was noticed coming from a IBC. Facilty personel placed sorbent and poly under the leaking IBC and notified the local managers.The container leak stopped when observed the following day. Given the wastes description  Clean Harbors Health & Safety and the NJ DEP were notified of the leaking IBC.All parties developed a plan to re-containerize the waste into the proper UN rated containers. With the NJ DEP present a few days later a response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment recontainerized the waste and loaded the containers for continued transportation to the intended disposal facility.NJ DEP report #14-08-28-1141-28
column169: Clean Harbors management met with the representaives of the generator/shipper and discussed proper UN rated shipping containers for further shipments of the waste. The generator agreed to ship the waste stream in these containers moving forward.

column168: R&L Carriers contacted ERTS at 10:10 EST to report the release on 55 gallons of UN1993 Flammable Liquid onto the floor of trailer OA1793 at the SAC Terminal, 1820 Parkway Blvd, West Sacramento, CA. It was reported that upon arrival the dock crew noticed the tote was leaking and noticed a crack in the upper left corner of tote. There is some liquid leaking from trailer and dock personnel placed absorbents onto ground to try and contain it.     An environmental contractor was dispatched to location and reported that only 15 gallons of product was released. The good product contained in impacted IBC was transferred to a replacement tote and sent on to the shipper.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: On August 29, 2014, USA Trucking reported the release of approximately 5 gallons of UN1263 Paint from multiple 5-gallon pails due to a load shift during transit. Cardno Environmental out of Bluefield, VA was dispatched to clean the release and over-pack any impacted pails. Upon Cardno's assessment, (8) 5-gallon plastic pails were identified to be damaged, but only (3) actually released paint. All (8) pails were over-packed into (3) 55-gallon steel drums and taken for proper disposal. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by this release; the release was contained to the trailer floor. The trailer was cleaned and re-loaded in accordance with state regulations.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: Vehicle was traveling North on an improved dirt road. Driver felt the shoulder of the road give way as it caved off into the road ditch. The driver attempted to compensate but over-steered which caused the pup trailer to go into the ditch and strike a tree. The impact with the tree compromised the top of the trailer resulting in damage and a small leak.
column169: Awareness training to drivers relative to poor road conditions and the hazards of driving too close to the edge oF unimproved roadways which are common to the oilfield environment.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: Package and inner shielded container was crushed and/or dragged by a tug and/or baggage carts. The vial in the inner shielded container was crushed resulting in radioactive contamination. The remnants of the package and the shielded inner container were recovered, placed in a plastic bag and will be returned to the sender in a salvage drum. An asphalt area approximately 5 feet x 12 feet in a covered area was found contaminated. The principally contaminated area was covered with steel plate to reduce radiation exposure and prevent the spread of contamination. Other areas were covered to prevent the spread of contamination. The restricted containment will remain in place for at least 16 days which will result the ln-111 to decay below an exempt quantity for use and possession under regulatory requirements. After at least 16 days the area will be resurveyed and released for unrestricted use if contamination levels are below regulatory limits.

column168: ON 7-29-14 AT 11:50, A SHIFTER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF PLACING TRAILER # UMXU 937146 ON BAY 6. column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: On August 27, 2014 at approximately 11:03 personnel in the CSXT Aliquippa Yard discovered UTLX 212891, a loaded tank car of Ammonia Solutions leaking vapors from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper Terra Pete Ruck- 847-405-2880, local, state and federal agencies as applicable were notified CHEMTREC Report # 2014082700180. SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 3 of 8 manway bolts less than tool tight. This car was a calf car that had trans loaded product in it that was secured from the trans load by SPSI. SPSI advised- that all the bolts were tight however they applied a lubricating agent and was able to tighten the bolts 3/4 of a turn and the vapor release stopped. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.    NARRI=200  5X (5+3+0) X (2+0) = 80

column168: A Clean Harbors employee was walking past Sea Container CMCU452414-6 which was staged inside the containment area earlier at the Bartow Facility when he noticed a small tan/creamish puddle which had an alcohol like odor underneath the container.  The Clean Harbors Response Team from the facility made an entry into the container  and found (2) 55 gallon Poly drums pressurized and bulging and (1) drum leaking from the bottom.  Absorbent material was placed around the leaking drum, the container was then offloaded.  The leaking drum and the 2 bulging drums were vented and placed into Salavge Drums. The container floor, the under carriage and the concrete were cleaned up and the residual and the PPE were place in appropriate containers to be disposed of properly.

Upon arrival at the pick up terminal, it was discovered that the weld around the valve of the tote was leaking. The spilled material was contained and the tote was patched. Due to the hazard of material, the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: Better inspection of totes can prevent this type of leak from happening. Specific inspection of valves and weld points for compromised tote integrity.

column168: Carrier’s driver was proceeding southbound on US-23.  An automobile lost control and struck the carrier’s vehicle on the right side, forcing the driver of the carrier’s vehicle to be pushed to the left and off of the roadway.  Once off of the roadway, the carrier’s vehicle rolled onto its right side.  Some of the IBCs (approximately 5) inside the carrier's trailer ruptured and approximately twenty-five (25) gallons of product leaked out.  Law enforcement and fire-rescue came upon the scene immediately.   The carrier immediately contacted all other necessary entities (the customer/shipper, the lead-logistics provider, Chemtrec, third party environmental company, and a towing and recovery company).    Fire-rescue oversaw the initial containment, and the third-party environmental company handled the eventual clean-up of the spill.  The towing/recovery company transloaded the remaining undamaged product into another trailer owned by the carrier, and it was brought back to the point of origin (i.e. the shipper).
column169: This incident was beyond the scope of the control of the carrier and the shipper.   It was an accident caused by another vehicle, and perhaps the packaging used was not designed to cutail a spill in the face of such an incident.

column168: Employee James Persons stated that he was driving Unit #B21 traveling South on 528 approaching 166 this is a 4 way intersection. N & S bound lanes have yellow flashing light and E & W have a red light, this direction must stop and yield. Employee had right of way. EE was approaching intersection and other vehicle pulled into intersection right in front of truck. Employee swerved to miss vehicle and went off the roadway. There was a leak from the pressure valve outside the truck. Employee stayed by the truck as the vapor cloud dissipated, (5 minutes) EE stated that the release was coming from the reel around the valve. Approx. 2 gallons released.
column169: The Company has a rollover prevention policy titled "Slip Off Stay Off" with cab posters and training reminders. The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn. After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts todetermine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our Employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to preventrollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: Technicians were doing truck-to-truck transfers of waste containers in preparation for final shipment of the hazardous waste to their designated disposal facility. At times, this includes transferring containers from one pallet to another. The drum in question was slid off the pallet by the technician onto the ground, a height of 4 inches. When the drum contacted the ground, a crack developed from the bottom, went about halfway up the drum and then went horizontal, several inches in each direction around the drum causing liquid to immediately release from the drum. The second technician rolled the drum so the crack was on top to prevent any further liquids from spilling out. Approximately, a third of the drum's contents were released as a consequence of the event. Sorbent socks and absorbent were immediately put in place to contain the spill. Management was notified. Employees suited up and cleaned up the spill and placed the damaged drum inside an overpack drum. The absorbent and clean-up material were added to the overpack drum. The spill was localized without any injury or environmental impact. The release did not pose a threat to public health, the environment, or equal or exceed a federal RQ.
column169: Employees were re-trained on container management and inspection with an emphasis on inspecting containers for signs of aging, deterioration and damage; along with a review of spill procedures during our monthly safety training meeting. There was a review of our internal SOP's as they relate to transfer procedures and spill response and being updated, accordingly. Spill equipment and berming practices were evaluated for appropriateness and effectiveness. As part of this corrective action, additional berming will be put in place this month.

column168: Carrier at consignee to off load, carrier opened internal valve, consignee noticed a small leak from the piping between the internal and external valve. Carrier closed the valve and the leak stopped. The consignee cleaned the spilled product with a neutralizer and decontaminated the CTMV. Carrier returned to carrier shop for repair. Carrier found the nipple fitting between the internal and external valve had a crack. The close nipple was replaced. Carrier returned to the consignee and completed off-loading with no issues. Event 42683

column168: CUSTOMER HAS A 5,000 TANK WHICH HAD IN IT 819 GALLONS, THIS WAS VERIFIED BEFORE OUR DELIVERY OF 2,500 GALLONS WAS RELEASED. DURING THE DELIVERY THE FUEL CAME SPRAYING OUT OF THE FILL PORT AT THE POINT OF 701 GALLONS DELIVERED, AND SPRAYED NEARBY CONCRETE, ASPHALT AND GARDEN AREA. ABOUT 10 GALLONS RAN INTO A NEARBY STORM DRAIN WHICH WAS A HOLDING STYLE DRAIN AND HAD NOT DISCHARGED BECAUSE IT WAS NOT FULL ENOUGH. OUR DRIVER, WHEN HE BECAME AWARE, SHUT DOWN THE FLOW OF PRODUCT AND IT WAS LATER LEARNED THAT A CAP WAS SCREWED ONTO THE TOP OF THE VENT, UNDERNEATH A SEPARATE SUMP COVER NEAR THE FILL PORT. WITH THE VENT BEING PLUGGED THE AIR IN THE TANK WAS NOT ABLE TO ESCAPE AND AS A RESULT, THE TANK OVER PRESSURIZED AND PRODUCT RELEASED THROUGH THE FILL PORT. IT WAS CONCLUDED THAT DURING SOME TYPE OF PREVIOUS SERVICE OR TESTING THE VENT CAP WAS PUT ONAND NEVER REMOVED. OUTSIDE CONTRACTORS WERE HIRED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND DISPOSE OF THE WASTE PROPERLY.

column168: UPON ARRIVING AT DELIVERY SITE, DRIVER BACK INTO CONTAINMENT PIT. column168: A Safety Kleen employee attempted to load a tote into a Box truck via the lift gate and the use of a pallet jack. The employee raised the lift gate and went to pull the pallet jack into the box truck when the wheels caught on the lip of the truck. The employee repositioned the pallet jack, and as he did the tote began to roll forward and falling off the lift gate.  The impact of the tote hitting the ground caused the cap to be dislodged from the tote, spilling approximately 15 gallons of material before the driver could re-attached the cap.  The material was contained in a concrete area inside the shipper's facility.  The spill was absorbed and cleaned up by Safety Kleen personnel and placed into appropriate DOT containers and the tote along with the clean up material were then sent for disposal.
column169: Recommended to the employee to use a forklift when loading totes if a dock is not available. If a forklift is not available the employee needs to get assistance when using the liftgate and pallett jack.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While traveling on Interstate 10 in New Orleans, Louisiana, tractor-trailer was involved in a rollover, which caused fire to ignite in vehicle. Approximately 8,660 gallons of gasoline were being transported at the time of the incident. An undetermined amount of gasoline was burnt up as a result of the fire, with the remaining product releasing to the soils adjacent to the roadway, and the nearby storm drain system. Local Fire Department responded to extinguish the fire, which caused the water run off and gasoline to migrate through the drainage system and release through the outfall. ES&H of Houma, Louisiana was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, ES&H used a vacuum truck to recover the free product from within the drainage system. ES&H proceeded to flush the drainage system and coordinated excavation of impacted soils within the woodland area adjacent the roadway. ES&H returned to the site on several occasions to excavate impacted soils, which were containerized into roll off boxes on site, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. ES&H also utilized a vacuum truck to recover the accumulated rain water from within excavation pits throughout remediation. Approximately 720 yards of contaminated soil, and 33,700 gallons of contaminated waters were generated during response efforts. Confirmation samples were pulled, and site will be restored to pre-existing condition, upon receipt of analytical sampling results. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While offloading at Shell Offload Station in Falls City, Texas, an overfill occurred, which resulted in the loss of approximately 2,300 gallons of crude oil. Free product released to the concrete surface and soil adjacent to the offloading area. Sage Envirotech was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Sage Envirotech recovered the free product from concrete surface and excavated the soils within loading area. The fill tanks were temporarily restaged to allow access to impacted area, and Sage Envirotech recovered all contaminated soils. Confirmation samples were pulled from excavation pit, and site was restored to preexisting condition. There was no impact to storm drain system, or state waters affected or threatened by the release. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column168: On 8/26/14, an Austin Powder Company dry bulk tank truck, originally laded with 40,000 lbs of ammonium nitrate, UN1942, was pneumatically unloading the material Into a vertical bin located at a surface coal mine near Phelps, KY, At 10:08 A.M. with about half of the AN unloaded, the driver noticed a sudden drop in engine rpm, and immediately shut-off the PTOs and engine to Investigate. He noticed white smoke coming from under the engine hood. When he lifted the hood, he noticed a fire, and went to the driver's side to retrieve a 20-lb ABC fire extinguisher. Upon return to the front of the vehicle, he determined the fire was unable to be extinguished, moved to a position of safety, and initiated his ERAP using his mobile phone. The mine was evacuated, and an initial evacuation area of V* mile established. MSHA Inspectors were on site and were immediately made aware of the incident. Emergency responders (Police and Fire) arrived. No attempt was made to re-enter the incident area to extinguish the fire. First responders evacuated nearby residences and stopped traffic. The company called their emergency spill and cleanup consultant who summoned their network contractor and their Independent Investigator to the mine.Clean up was held up while MSHA investigated, while the independent investigator conducted his analysis. The AN was not damaged, and was off-loaded into a mine blasting truck, and used as originally intended in blasting. The fire debris was cleaned up by the spill contractor, and the truck body and engine/transmission were removed from the mine.

column168: ON 8/22/2014 AMEROCHEM CORPORATION DRIVER J. BARBER PICKED UP 150 (COUNT) DOT SPEC CYLINDERS FILLED WITH CHLORINE, UN 1017 FROM JCI CHEMICAL INC. REPACKAGING PLANT IN MILFORD, VA. JCI IS A REPACKAGER, SHIPPER AND OWNER OF THE CYLINDERS. AMEROCHEM WAS ACTING AS A PRIVATE CARRIER AND DISTRIBUTOR FOR THE CYLINDERS. THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING DIRECTLY ROUNTED TO THE AMEROCHEM LOCATION IN NEW BERN, NC. DURING A FUEL STOP NEAR EMPORIA, VA OFF I-95 THE DRIVER SMELLED CHLORINE AND FOUND A STRONG ODOR OF CHLORINE IN THE TRAILER. HE MOVED THE TRAILER AWAY FROM THE FUEL AREA AND CALLED HIS DISPATCHER AND 911. A RESPONSE TEAM FROM JCI FOUND A CYLINDER WAS LATER RETURNED TO JCI, MILLFORD WHO REPORTED A WEIGHT LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 30 POUNDS BY WEIGHT DIFFERENTIAL. JCI PROVIDED INFORMATION ON THE NATURE OF THE FAILURE THAT APPEARED TO BE INTERANL CORROSION OF THE FUSE PLUG FROM MOISTURE CONTAMINATION.
column169: AMEROCHEM COPRORATION INSTITUTED A PROCEDURE TO VAPOR TEST ALL CYLINDERS AS THEY ARE LOADED FOR PICK UP. THE SHIPPER JCI JONES CHEMICALS, NOTIFIED THE CARRIER OF SEVERAL OPERATIONAL UPDATES TO THEIR INSPECTION PROCEDURES IN THE REPACKAGING PROCESS INCLUDING REPLACEMENT OF THE HIGH INTENSITY INSPECTION LIGHT AND EMPLOYEE RETRAINING.

column168: Investigation of odor led to the discovery of approximately one quart (four cups) of crude oil relased to the top of the tank car from the manway nozzle.  Inspection of the manway found there was no gasket. A new gasket was placed on the manway nozzle and the manway secured.  Inspection of the remainder of the tank car found approximately one cup of crude oil had released from the bottom outlet valve packing gland, covering the bottom outlet nozzle and cap, and dripping to the ground below. Packing nuts were tightened 1/2 turn each stopping the release.
column169: Proper inspection of all nozzles, valves and fitting during or after load/unload and prior to transportation.

column168: WHILE DELIVERING A DRUM TO SMETHPORT, PA ON A VAN WITH A LIFT GATE, OUR DRIVER ACCIDENTALLY PUNCTURED THE LOWER PART OF THE PLASTIC (55 GALLON) DRUM HE WAS MOVING. THE PUNCTURE OCCURED WHEN THE FOOT OF THE DRUM CART DRIVER WAS USING TO MOVE THE DRUM CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE LOWER QUARTER OF THE DRUM WITH FORCE IN AN EFFORT TO MANIPULATE THE DRUMS POSITION. THE PUNCTURE WAS APPROX. 1 INCH IN LENGTH AND A 1/4 INCH IN HEIGHT. AN ESTIMATE 3 GALLONS OF HYPO WERE LOST ONTO THE LIFT GATE OF VAN. IMMEDIATE ACTION TO MITIGATION THE LEAK WAS TAKEN BY TURNING THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE AND MOVING IT TO A CONTAINMENT AREA WHERE IT WAS TRANSFERRED TO A NEW DRUM. CLEANUP COMMENCED IMMEDIATELY AND WITH CLEAN RAGS AND WATER THE 3 GALLONS WERE CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF.
column169: THERE WERE NO CHANGES MADE TO THE PACKAGING OF DELIVERY METHOD AT THIS PARTICULAR LOCATION. A DRUM CART SERVES A SPECIFIC PURPOSE AND WHEN USED OUTSIDE OF THE PURPOSE ACCIDENTS SUCH AS THIS WILL OCCUR.

column168: ON AUGUST 13,2014 DURING A HEAVY RAINFALL EVENT, A DELANEY FUEL TRANSPORT, LLC(DFT) REPRESENTATIVE WAS TRANSFERRING GASOLINE FROM A TANKER TRUCK TO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. IT IS HYPOTHESIZED THAT WHEN THE REPRESENTATIVE CONNECTED THE HOSE TO THE TANKER, THE CAM FITTINGS WERE NOT FULLY IN THE CLOSED POSITION. AT THE END OF THE DELIVERY, THE HOSE DISCONNECTED FROM THE LOADING HEAD (TANKER SIDE) AND GASOLINE DRAINED OUT OF THE HOSE AND PIPE/LOADING HEAD. BASED ON EVIDENCE AFTER THE SPILL, DFT ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 29 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS SPILLED ON TO THE CONCRETE TANK PAD. THE SPILLED GASOLINE FLOWED ON AND WITH RAIN WATER ACROSS THE CONCRETE TANK PAD, ASPHALT DRIVEWAY, ON TO TOWER ROAD, AND INTO ONE OR MORE CATCH BASINS. THE CATCH BASINS ARE LOCATED AT THE INTERSECTION ON TOWER ROAD AND MAIN STREET. THE HUDSON FIRE DEPARTMENT REQUIRED REPRESENTATIVES AT THE FURNITURE MANUFACTURING COMPANY, AIS, LOCATED AT 54 CHERRY STREET, TO EVACUATE THE BUILDING DUE TO AN ELEVATED LOWER EXPLOSIVE LEVEL READING IN THE BUILDING DURING THE EARLY STAGES OF RESPONSE ACTIONS. SORBENT HARD AND SOFT BOOM WERE PLACED ACROSS THE OUTFALL WHERE THE DRAIN DISCHARGES INTO THE ASSABET RIVER. STORM DRAINS WERE ALSO VENTED.
column169: PRIOR TO STARTING A PICK UP OR DELIVERY, THE DRIVER SHOULD INSPECT THE HOSES AND ASSOCIATED MALE AND FEMALE FITTINGS. THE INSPECTION SHOULD INCLUDE EXAMINING GASKETS, CAM LOCKS FOR CLEAN RANGE OF MOVEMENT, AND LOOKING FOR EVIDENCE OF WEAR ON THE FITTINGS, CAM LOCKS AND GASKETS. REPLACE PARTS THAT APPEAR TO BE DAMAGED, WORN OR DO NOT MOVE CLEANLY.

On 8/17/2014, QC Energy Resources Texas, LLC contacted ERTS in regards to a crude oil release at the Harding Well Site. It was reported that approximately 3 barrels, 130 gallons, of crude oil was released during loading of the CTMV. The driver forgot to shut the pump off which resulted in an over fill. The release impacted the soil around the pumping station. ERTS dispatched a contractor to the site for initial response and remediation activities. The contractors vacuumed up the free product from the dirt. A mini-excavator was used to scrape up the impacted dirt.

column168: OUR REGIONAL SAFETY MGR, DONALD BOYER, RECEIVED A CALL AT APPROXIMATELY 16:30 HOURS THAT A LIQUID TRANSPORT CORP TANKER TRUCK HAD ROLLED OVER IN THE MEDIAN ON INTERSTATE 10 EASTBOUND NEAR WELSH, LA AT MILE MARKER 5. DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT IN THE CARGO TANK WAS TRICHLOROETHYLENE AND WAS NOTIFIED FROM LOCAL AUTHORITIES THAT CARGO TANK WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE "DOME LID" OF THE TRAILER.  NOTIFIED DIRECTOR OF SAFETY, JOEL PASKA, OF THE SPILL AND THE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. JOEL CONTACTED HAZMAT ONE TO HANDLE THE REMEDIATION. ES&H FROM LAKE CHARLES, LA WAS CONTACTED AS THE LOCAL COMPANY TO ASSIST IN THE SPILL AND THE REMEDIATION OF THE CONTAMINATED GROUND. AN ADDITIONAL CARGO TANK TRUCK WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE TO OFF LOAD THE REMAINING PRODUCT AND STOP THE LEAK FROM THE DOME LID AREA. ES&H USED ABSORPTION BOOMS IN THE CONTAMINATED AREA TO STOP THE PRODUCT FROM MIGRATING. ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERS (BURNS & MCDONNELL) HAVE BEEN BROUGHT IN TO TAKE GROUND SAMPLES OF THE CONTAMINATED AREA, DETERMINE DEPTH OF GROUND WATER TABLE AND PROPOSE REMEDIATION PLANS (FOR REMOVAL OF SOIL AND TRAFFIC CONTROL WHILE WORKING ON THE HIGHWAY.) THIS IS AN ONGOING PROCESS. WE ARE WORKING CLOSELY WITH THE LOUISIANAN DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.
column169: CONTINUE TO HAVE SAFETY MEETINGS WITH ALL DRIVERS TO DISCUSS PROPER SPEED/SPACE MANAGEMTN TECHNIQUES WHILE TRANSPORTING CHEMICAL PRODUCTS ON HIGHWAYS.  SPECIFICALLY DISCUSS THIS INCIDENT AND EXPLAIN THE ENVIRONMENTAL, FINANCIAL AND PERSONAL RAMIFICATIONS OF THIS ACCIDENT.  SAFETY ON THE HIGHWAY IS THE NUMBER ONE PRIORITY.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 ON AUGUST 9, 2014, A TRUCK DRIVER ARRIVED AT SEVERSTAL WITH A TRUCK LOAD OF HYDROCHOLORIC ACID SOLUTION. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED SEVERSTAL PERSONNEL OF HIS ARRIVAL AND SEVERSTAL PERSONNEL VERIFIED THE DRIVER WAS HOOKED UP PROPERLY FOR THE UNLOADING PROCESS. THE DRIVER BEGAN THE UNLOADING PROCESS AND RETURNED TO HIS TRUCK. APPROXIAMATELY FIVE MINUTES LATER, A SEVERSTAL EMPLOYEE NOTICED ACID LEAKING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRUCK. THE DRIVER WAS ALERTED OF THE SITUATION AND PROMPTLY CLOSED THE VALVE. UPON INSPECTION, THE CLAMP USED TO ATTACH THE UNLOADING HOSE TO THE TRUCK WAS CRACKED. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED UNTIL GROUND TESTED A NEUTRAL PH. THE STORM WATER AND PROCESS WATER DITCHES WERE MONITORED FOR PH FOR AN ADDITIONAL 8 HOURS.
column169: SEVERSTAL'S POLICY IS FOR TRUCK DRIVERS TO REMAIN OUTSIDE THEIR TRUCK AND IN DIRECT SUPERVISION OF THE UNLOADING PROCESS AT ALL TIMES. THIS POLICY HAS BEEN REITERATED WITH ALL TRUCKING COMPANIES THAT OPERATE ON SITE.

column168: OUR OPERATOR SUSPECTED THERE WAS FIRE ON OR AT THE TRUCK ENGINE. HE STOPPED ON THE EMERGENCY LANE AND BEGAN ATTEMPTS TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE (20LB. FIRE EXTINGUISHER). THE FIRE WAS TOO LARGE & INTENSE FOR OPENING OF THE TRUCKS HOOD: WHICH HAMPERED HIS EFFORTS TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE WHICH WAS STILL AT OR ON THE ENGINE; HAVING EXHAUSTED THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER HE CALLED ME. THE HEAT BEGAN TO MELT THE TANKER; RELEASING THE GASOLINE & INTENSIFYING THE FIRE. MOST OF THE GASOLINE BURNED AS IT WAS RELEASED. SOME GASOLINE DID PENETRATE SOIL IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA; NONE FLOWED FAR FROM THE RELEASE POINT. DURATION OF RELEASE TIME APPROX 1 1/2 HOUR. column169: THE FIRE STARTED ON OR NEAR THE TRUCK ENGINE. WE ARE STRESSING EXAMINATION OF ELECTRICAL CALBLES INSULATION, FUEL LINES, ETC. WE DO NOT KNOW THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE INITIAL FIRE; WHEN THE FIRE WAS FINALLY BURNED OUT & OR EXTINGUISHED NOTHEING EXCEPT STEEL COMPONENTS AND THE FRAME AND LOWEST PORTION OF THE ALUMINUM TANKER TRAILER WAS STILL IN TACT.

column168: Shipment originated at 3M Co in Forest City, IA on 8/22/14 and moved to our Des Moines, IA terminal where it was loaded on a trailer destined for Lyons, IL. The shipment was checked in at our Lyons, IL terminal with a notation of carton damage. The direct cause of the carton damage is unknown at this time. There was no visible signs that the product inside was damaged or had leaked. The shipment was then loaded and secured for delivery to Alexian Brothers Medical Center in Elk Grove Village, IL. An employee at Alexian Brothers Medical Center opened the carton and discovered 2 of the canisters had leaked. The carton was immediately quarantined to a safe location. There are no reported symptoms of exposure or injuries as a result of this incident.
column169: As a transporter of hazardous materials we understand the importance of making sure all hazmat employees receive proper training. We are in the process of retraining all employees on the proper procedures for transporting UN 1040 Ethylene Oxide 2.3 (2.1). Proper load securement is a vital component for handling hazardous materials and is a top priority at our company. Our trailers are equipped with both vertical and horizontal tracks. We utilize load bars, straps and dunnage to help insure the safe transportation of hazardous materials. We value life and the safety of all and will do our best to prevent any future reoccurrences.

column168: On August 14, 2014 at 07:12, at the beginning of offloading HiTEC 6591N Fuel Additive from the tank truck to the terminal at 175 Front Street in South Portland, ME 04106, pressure built up in the hose and the connection fitting failed and released approximately 23 gallons to the loading rack area. When the release was observed, the valve was closed and the pumps were shut down to stop product flow. The product moved to the trench drains in the loading rack secondary containment area. The separator outfall was closed and Clean Harbors was called to the facility to conduct cleanup activities, which included using a vacuum truck to remove product and water from the trench drains, deploying absorbent pads to absorb residual product, and completing a hot pressure wash of the area. Approximately 823 gallons of product and water mixture and approximately 100 pounds (4 bags) of oily solids (absorbent pads) were removed and sent off-site for proper disposal.
column169: Appropriate offloading procedures were followed. The cause of the release was equipment malfunction. Repairs were made to fix the equipment and is now working properly.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Rollover Accident
column168: OUR TRAILER WAS TRAVELING E/B AT ABOUT 35 MPH DUE TO A BAD TIRE LOOKING FOR A SAFE PLACE TO PULL OFF THE ROAD WHEN THE OTHER TRUCK WHICH WAS TRAVELING AT ABOUT 70 MPH. THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER TRUCK INDICATED HE LOOKED BACK INTO THE SLEEPER BERTH MOMENTARILY AND WHEN HE LOOKED BACK JUST PRIOR TO IMPACTING OUR UNIT. column168: ON AUGUST 12,2014 FINCH FUEL WAS MAKING A ROUTINE DELIVERY OF #2 DYED DIESEL FUEL TO A UST LOCATED AT 86 RIVER ROAD, MONTVILLE NJ. DURING DELIVERY THE UST WAS OVERFILLED RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 438-GALLONS (BASED ON INVENTORY RECORDS AND INTERVIEWS WITH PERSONNEL). DIESEL FUEL FLOWED ACROSS A PAVED SURFACE, ENTERED A STORM DRAIN AND FLOWED INTO THE ROCKAWAY RIVER. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM MORRIS COUNTY RESPONDED ALONG WITH RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM ATLANTIC RESPONSE INC. CONTAINMENT BOOMS AND ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE PLACED IN THE RIVER AND THE STORM DRAIN TO CONTAIN AND COLLECT THE DIESEL FUEL. THE NJDEP WAS NOTIFIED AND CLEANUP UNDER THE NJDEP LSRP PROGRAM WAS IMPLEMENTED. A VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED TO COLLECT FUEL FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREAS. ALL SITE WORK WAS/IS BEING COMPLETED UNDER THE DIRECT SUPERVISION OF NJDEP EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL AS WELL AS THE MORRIS COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM. PERSONNEL HIRED BY FINCH FUEL AND THEIR INSURANCE PROVIDER ARE CURRENTLY COMPLETING SITE ACTIVITIES UNDER THE NJDEP LSRP CLEANUP PROGRAM.    THE RELEASE WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE RESULT OF THE FINCH DRIVERS DELIVERING TO THE WRONG TANK. INVESTIGATIONS CONDUCTED DETERMINED THAT THE DELIVERY SHOULD HAVE BEEN MADE TO A UST AT 143 RIVER ROAD, MONTVILLE NJ AND NOT 86 RIVER ROAD. NOTE BOTH FACILITIES ARE MONTVILLE NJ DPW FACILITIES.
column169: THE ACCIDENTAL RELEASE WAS REVIEWED WITH THE FINCH FUEL DRIVERS AND PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN PUT IN PLACE FOR DRIVERS TO VERIFY THE LOCATION OF THEIR DELIVERIES PRIOR TO COMMENCING. DRIVERS WERE ALSO ADVISED TO VERIFY THE SIXE OF THE UST PRIOR TO MAKING THE DELIVERY AS WELL AS VERIFYING MEASUREMENTS OF FREE SPACE IN THE TANK PRIOR TO COMMENCING DELIVERY.

column168: DRIVER OF FUEL DELIVERY VEHICLES WAS NORTH BOUND ON 30TH STREET NORTHWEST AND HAD STOPPED ON THE EDGE OF THE ROAD AS THE ROAD WAS NARROW AND THERE WAS ANOTHER VEHICLE TRAVELING SOUTH. DRIVER WAITED FOR THE SOUTHBOUND VEHICLE (A PICKUP TRUCK) TO PASS AND THEN BEGAN MOVING SLOWLY FORWARD IN THE NORTHBOUND DIRECTION. WHEN HE PULLED FORWARD THE FRONT RIGHT TIRE OF THE VEHICLE WENT DOWN IN THE DITCH HOWEVER THERE WAS NO SHOULDER ON THIS AREA OF THE ROAD AND THE DRIVER COUND NOT TELL THERE WAS NO SHOULDER AS THE GRASS APPEARED TO BE ALL THE SAME HEIGHT. WHEN THE FRONT TIRE WENT DOWN THE DRIVER FELL THE FUEL IN THE TRUCK SHIFT AND IN SLOW MOTION THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER AND ENDED UP WHEELS UP IN A SLOUGH OF WATER.   THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND RURAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED OF THE ACCIDENT AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY PUT OUT BARRIERS AROUND THE TRUCK TO CONTAIN ANY POTENTIAL PRODUCT THAT MAY LEAK. NONE OF THE TANKS PUNCTURED OR RUPTURED.  THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF FUEL THAT LEAKED OUT THE TRUCK WHILE THE TRUCK WAS IN THE UPSIDE DOWN POSITION. ONCE THE TRUCK WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH THE FUEL WAS METERED OFF. TOTAL FUEL LOST FROM THE AMOUNT METERED ON THE TRUCK PRE-ACCIDENT TO THE AMOUNT METERED OFF THE TRUCK POST ACCIDENT WAS 28.2 GALLONS.  EARTHMOVERS, A LOCAL CERTIFIED CLEANUP COMPANY CAME IN AND CLEANED UP ALL LOST FUEL. THEY PUT OUT ABSORPTION PADS AND IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND SOAKED UP ALMOST ALL OF THE FUEL. EARTHMOVERS DID OPEN THE AREA SOME SO THAT THEY COULD FULLY CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.
column169: THE INCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED WITH THE DRIVER. THE DRIVER FELT HE WAS TAKING GREAT PRECAUTIONS AS HE HAD STOPPED IN THE ROAD TO ALLOW THE OTHER VEHICLE TO PASS IN ORDER TO BE SAF. SINCE THE INCIDENT THE DRIVER NO LONGER USES 30TH STREET NORTHWEST TO GET TO THE JOB SITE BUT RATHER USES A DIFFERENT, WIDER ROAD. WE ALSO DISCUSSEED AN ACTION PLAN OF BEING AWARE OF THE SURROUNDINGS AND AMOUNT OF DITCH, SLOPE, ETC. TO AVOID THIS TYPE OF ACCIDENT AGAIN.

Mr. Evon dropped off a shipment of household goods to be shipped to Anchorage. Upon physically searching the shipment several incidences of dangerous goods were found in the shipment (including: ammunition, gun oil solvent, loose batteries, aerosols, and flammable liquids). Removed the dangerous goods from shipment and placed shipment on hold.
column169: Better postings for dangerous goods located in cargo office.

column168: Employee arrived at storage tank to load gasoline. Due to employee failure/error, he opened the wrong hatch cover and was sprayed in the face with a small amount of gasoline that was heated. No significant amount of material was released. Employee suffered minor burns to the face as well as eye and respiratory exposure from vapors. Employee was transported via company vehicle to the nearest treatment facility where he was treated and released. Later the employee returned and was admitted for observation due to respiratory symptoms. Employee was released to full duty a few days later with no follow-up required.     This incident was not reported via telephone due to error. The initial report was that he had been treated and released. Also this incident did not occur during transportion and it was later that it was realized that it most likely fit the category of "storage incident to transportation" - so the report is now being submitted.

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC UNIT WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON I-75 ON SARASOTA, FLORIDA. DUE TO AN APPARENT MEDICAL, THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL AND WENT ACROSS THE CENTER MEDIAN AND THE NORTHBOUND LANES AND ULTIMATELY ROLLED OVER UPON HITTING THE SOFT SHOULDER. AS A RESULT OF THE ROLLOVER, THE TANK WAS COMPROMISED AND APPROXIMATELY 1800 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC IS STILL EVALUATING ANY RESIDUAL IMPACT FROM THE GASOLINE SPILL.
column169: KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE DRIVING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Rollover Accident
column168: ON AUGUST 18, 2014 AT APPROXIMATELY 1635 HOURS I, OFFICER FREDERICK RESPONDED TO A SINGLE VEHICLE ROLL OVER CRASH ON SUMMERVILLE ROAD AT 30TH STREET.  UPON ARRIVAL I SPOKE WITH ORLANDO LAMOURT DRIVER OF UNIT 1 AND HE STATED THAT HE WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON SUMMERVILLE ROAD.  MR LAMOURT STATED THAT HE WAS ATTEMPTING TO SLOW DOWN AS HE NEGOTIATED THE CURVE.  MR LAMOURT STATED THAT HE DIDN'T KNOW WHAT HAPPENED BUT DROVE OFF THE ROADWAY AND OVER TURNED HIS VEHICLE.    MR LAMOURT WAS TRANSPORTED BY CARE AMBULANCE TO MIDTOWN MEDICAL CENTER.    UNIT 1 WAS TOWED FROM SCENE BY BI-CITY TOWING.
